Adding hydroxyl groups to the phenyl ring, as seen in epinephrine, increases hydrogen bonding capabilities which typically raises the melting point. Considering the strong intermolecular hydrogen bonding due to the hydroxyl groups, we can estimate an increase of about 5°C for each hydroxyl group. Additionally, the amine group in epinephrine also participates in hydrogen bonding, which can further increase the melting point, but to a lesser extent than a hydroxyl group, thus an estimate of 2°C increase for the amine group is made.
